    <text>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_4699b149">
            <lb />
            <hi rendition="#c">
                The Welte-Mignon
                <lb />Has a Faculty
                <lb />of One Hundred and Fifty-Six
                <lb />Instructors in Piano Playing
            </hi>
        </div>
        <div facs="#eSc_textblock_4402ea80">
            <seg ana="#educational_use" resp="#np" type="topic">
                <lb />The Welte-Mignon can be likened to a college for teaching
                <lb />the art of playing the piano.
                <lb />This college has a faculty of one hundred fifty-six instructors-the
                <lb />leading pianists of this generation.
                <lb />These master pianists have interpreted over five thousand different
                <lb />pieces of the best musical literature of all ages of which each inter-
                <lb />pretation is an authoritative instruction in
                <lb />the playing off that particular composition
                <lb />-a final lesson in the art of finished piano playing.
                <lb /> playing.
                <lb />The Welte-Mignon is the means
                <lb />through which this great storehouse of cor-
                <lb />rect and artistic piano playing is given to
                <lb />the public-the student and layman, alike.
                <lb />All of the great musical conservatories of
                <lb />the world, if taken together, could not com-
                <lb />mand a faculty of such combined power
                <lb />and genius as the faculty of piano inter-
                <lb />pretation employed by the Welte-
                <lb />Mignon.
                <lb />Nor can all the combined musical schools find it within
                <lb />their means to render the great masterpieces of musical
                <lb />literature with such authority as can the Welte
                <lb />Mignon.
            </seg>
        </div>
